18.Strain Gauges

What Is It?

a strain gauge is a resistor consisting of a flexible film material

used to measure the strain of a material

mechanical strain is

$$ \varepsilon = \frac{\Delta \ell}{\ell} $$
Figure 1: Strain Gauge
Figure 2: Strain Gauge Patterns

At the ends of these pattern are terminals which are sometimes called pads

The pads are the location of where wire extension leads will be solder

How Does It Work?

The strain gauge is first glued on to a member that experiences strain

In industry, there are very particular ways in which the strain gauge must be glued

For this course's purposes, super glue will be adequate in the adhesion of the strain gauge to the member

It is well known that a material's resistance is determined by the material's length $ L $, cross-section $ A $, and resistivity $ \rho $

Resistivity is a material property that is tabulated

$$ R = \rho \frac{L}{A} $$

When the strain gauge is not experiencing strain, the resistance of the strain gauge is known as the nominal resistance $ R_o $

A widespread nominal resistance $ R_o $ is $ 120 \Omega $

Figure 3: Strain Gauge In Tension

The strain gauge is stretched in tension

the zig-zag pattern lines elongate

while the cross-sectional area narrows

The tension produces an increase in resistance

This change is denoted as $ \Delta R $

Figure 4: Strain Gauge In Compression

the strain gauge is compressed

the zig-zag pattern lines shorten

the cross-sectional area thickens

The compression produces a decrease in resistance

The changes in resistance $ \Delta R $ is related to the strain experienced by

$$ \varepsilon = \frac{\frac{\Delta R}{R_o}}{GF} $$

$ \Delta R $ is the change in resistance

$ R_o $ is the nominal resistance

$ GF $ is the strain gauge's gauge factor

The gauge factor $ GF $ is a proportional constant that is decided in the strain gauge design phase

a widespread gauge factor $ GF $ is approximately $ 2.1 $

The gauge factor may be found from the strain gauge manufacturer's datasheet

While strain $ \varepsilon $ is a significant quantity to know about a member, stress $ \sigma $ is typically the desired quantity

uniaxial stress $ \sigma $ is

$$ \sigma = E \varepsilon $$

$ E $ is the modulus of elasticity

The change in resistance $ \Delta R $ of a strain gauge will often be very small for even large strain situations

Typically a voltage divider circuit is implemented to measure resistance as a change of voltage

in this case, a voltage divider circuit is not well suited

To overcome this limitation, a Wheatstone bridge circuit is often used

Wheatstone Bridge

Figure 5: Wheatstone Bridge Circuit
Figure 6: Wheatstone Bridge Circuit Alternate View

The current through the left voltage divider circuit $ I_{abc} $ is

$$ I_{abc} = \frac{V_e}{R_{ab} + R_{bc}} $$
$$ V_b = I_{abc} R_{bc} = \frac{V_e R_{bc}}{R_{ab} + R_{bc}} $$

A similar process may be taken to find the voltage at node $ D $

$$ I_{adc} = \frac{V_e}{R_{ad} + R_{cd}} $$
$$ V_d = I_{adc} R_{cd} = \frac{V_e R_{cd}}{R_{ad} + R_{cd}} $$

The output voltage $ V_o $ is then

$$ V_o = V_d - V_b = \frac{V_e R_{cd}}{R_{ad} + R_{cd}} - \frac{V_e R_{bc}}{R_{ab} + R_{bc}} = V_e \frac{R_{ab}R_{cd} - R_{bc}R_{ad}}{\left(R_{ad} + R_{cd}\right)\left(R_{ab} + R_{bc}\right)} $$

What would the output voltage be if all the resistances where equal (i.e. $ R_{ab} = R_{bc} = R_{cd} = R_{ad} $ )?

This state is known as a balanced Wheatstone bridge circuit

An imbalanced Wheatstone bridge is one where the output voltage $ V_o $ is not zero

An imbalance may occur in one of two ways

The first way, which is typically not desired, is due to differences in the rated value of a resistor

This type of imbalance may be overcome by replacing one of the resistors in the Wheatstone bridge circuit with a potentiometer

Figure 6: Wheatstone Bridge Circuit with potentiometer

The resistance of the potentiometer $ R_p $ may be adjusted to balance an imbalanced Wheatstone bridge circuit

The second type of imbalance results from a change in resistance value of one or more of the resistors

Ideally, only one resistor value would change at a time

let's say that the resistor $ R_{cd} $ experiences a change in resistance $ \Delta R $ from its nominal value of $ R_o $

$$ R_{cd} = R_o + \Delta R $$

The output voltage $ V_o $ may then be written as

$$ V_o = V_e \frac{R_{ab}\left(R_o + \Delta R\right)- R_{bc}R_p}{\left(R_p + R_o + \Delta R\right)\left(R_{ab} + R_{bc}\right)} $$

Solving for the change in resistance $ \Delta R $ yields

$$ \Delta R = \frac{V_e \left( R_{ab}R_o - R_{bc}R_p \right) - V_o \left( R_{ab} + R_{bc} \right)\left( R_p + R_o \right)}{V_o \left( R_{ab} + R_{bc} \right) - V_e R_{ab}} $$

A strain gauge may replace the resistor $ R_{cd} $ with a resistance of $ R_g $

Figure 7: Wheatstone Bridge Circuit with strain gauge

This type of Wheatstone bridge configuration is known as a quarter-bridge
